251	/* Return the command time snapshot in milliseconds.
252	 * The time the command started is the logical time it runs,
253	 * and all the time readings during the execution time should
254	 * reflect the same time.
255	 * More details can be found in the comments below. */
256	mstime_t commandTimeSnapshot(void) {
257	    /* When we are in the middle of a command execution, we want to use a
258	     * reference time that does not change: in that case we just use the
259	     * cached time, that we update before each call in the call() function.
260	     * This way we avoid that commands such as RPOPLPUSH or similar, that
261	     * may re-open the same key multiple times, can invalidate an already
262	     * open object in a next call, if the next call will see the key expired,
263	     * while the first did not.
264	     * This is specifically important in the context of scripts, where we
265	     * pretend that time freezes. This way a key can expire only the first time
266	     * it is accessed and not in the middle of the script execution, making
267	     * propagation to slaves / AOF consistent. See issue #1525 for more info.
268	     * Note that we cannot use the cached server.mstime because it can change
269	     * in processEventsWhileBlocked etc. */
270	    return server.cmd_time_snapshot;
271	}
