2827	/* Every call to this function, will make the string 'str' requiring
2828	 * an additional call to RedisModule_FreeString() in order to really
2829	 * free the string. Note that the automatic freeing of the string obtained
2830	 * enabling modules automatic memory management counts for one
2831	 * RedisModule_FreeString() call (it is just executed automatically).
2832	 *
2833	 * Normally you want to call this function when, at the same time
2834	 * the following conditions are true:
2835	 *
2836	 * 1. You have automatic memory management enabled.
2837	 * 2. You want to create string objects.
2838	 * 3. Those string objects you create need to live *after* the callback
2839	 *    function(for example a command implementation) creating them returns.
2840	 *
2841	 * Usually you want this in order to store the created string object
2842	 * into your own data structure, for example when implementing a new data
2843	 * type.
2844	 *
2845	 * Note that when memory management is turned off, you don't need
2846	 * any call to RetainString() since creating a string will always result
2847	 * into a string that lives after the callback function returns, if
2848	 * no FreeString() call is performed.
2849	 *
2850	 * It is possible to call this function with a NULL context.
2851	 *
2852	 * When strings are going to be retained for an extended duration, it is good
2853	 * practice to also call RedisModule_TrimStringAllocation() in order to
2854	 * optimize memory usage.
2855	 *
2856	 * Threaded modules that reference retained strings from other threads *must*
2857	 * explicitly trim the allocation as soon as the string is retained. Not doing
2858	 * so may result with automatic trimming which is not thread safe.
2859	 *
2860	 * This API is not thread safe, access to these retained strings (if they originated
2861	 * from a client command arguments) must be done with GIL locked. */
2862	void RM_RetainString(RedisModuleCtx *ctx, RedisModuleString *str) {
2863	    if (ctx == NULL || !autoMemoryFreed(ctx,REDISMODULE_AM_STRING,str)) {
2864	        /* Increment the string reference counting only if we can't
2865	         * just remove the object from the list of objects that should
2866	         * be reclaimed. Why we do that, instead of just incrementing
2867	         * the refcount in any case, and let the automatic FreeString()
2868	         * call at the end to bring the refcount back at the desired
2869	         * value? Because this way we ensure that the object refcount
2870	         * value is 1 (instead of going to 2 to be dropped later to 1)
2871	         * after the call to this function. This is needed for functions
2872	         * like RedisModule_StringAppendBuffer() to work. */
2873	        incrRefCount(str);
2874	    }
2875	}
